<br>
and  &quot;lowtax's opinon, always worth a read&quot;<br>
<br>
That stupid drivel was a waste of the 3 minutes I took to read it.  But then, I should not expect to hear something worthwhile from someone who simply makes inflammatory and/or innane statements for the express purpose of drumming up publicity.  Mocking the Catholic Church (And any organized religion for that matter.) is en vogue right now and I've heard the exact same &quot;summary of a day in a Catholic Church&quot; applied to Southern Baptists, Jehovah's Witnesses, Mennonites, Hasidic Jews, Muslims, and so on down the religious line that it did not strike me as original, witty, humorous, or insightful.<br>
<br>
Gaelron states:  &quot;I won't state my opinion on this subject for the time being cause I know how people fiercely believe in their religions and want to see how the diverse EQ community feels.&quot;<br>
<br>
You want to know what I think about this ruling, well here goes.<br>
<br>
Do I think the pledge itself is unconstitutional?  No.  It's an oath of loyalty to this nation.  The phrase &quot;under God&quot; is in reference to some of the reasons this country was founded and was added in to distinguish us from countries who oppress those who do believe in a god.  <br>
<br>
I think forcing anyone to recite the Pledge of Allegiance is unconstitutional unless said person is becoming a naturalized citizen, joining the military or some occupation that involves the defense and/or security of this nation.  If you can't swear some level of loyalty to this country because you have a personal hang-up about the concept of a god, or absolutely hate the idea that the majority of people 'on this planet' believe in a higher power, then you have no business working in a field that involves protecting this country and its inhabitants.<br>
<br>
As much as these self-proclaimed aethists, agnostics, politically correct leftists etc. want to scream otherwise, this country was founded by people who believed and worshipped the &quot;Christian&quot; god.  And quite frankly I resent their attempts to force me to accept and recognize their religious beliefs (or lack thereof) as superior to mine.  They're no better than the religious groups they accuse of infringing on their rights.<br>
<br>
Offhand, I don't recall any specific reference to God in the Constitution other than the prohibition of making laws to favor one religion over another or requiring a religion test for someone seeking public office but Article V is in place to allow for any changes in the Constitution if someone wants to try and have it stricken from the document.  Personlly, it won't surprise me next to hear the courts demand that history books which indicate that the Pilgrims came to this country fleeing religious persecution be removed from public schools and libraries because of its references to god.  To be followed by removal of all books that refer to god or a godlike entity. Then moving on to anything written by people known for their religious beliefs and so forth and so on.  Perhaps Ray Bradbury wasn't too far off in Farenheit 451.<br>
<br>
<br>
